This is my origin story. I was in Junior Year English as a Freshman and knew I was going to fail because of exactly this

Crazy what time does. In the beginning of 2020 my brother was charged with 2nd Degree Murder, 2nd Degree Assault, Conspiracy and Concealing Evidence. He was cleared off every charge except 2nd Degree Assault for which he is now serving 18 years. In that time, I bought a house, had a kid, moved to The Bay and took my daughter to Australia for two months. This was the first time he got to see his niece and they hit it off immediately.

This is a hot tip for everyone. Surround yourself with as many good fathers as you can. Not everyone has the privilege but, if you find one, do what you can to latch on to them and pick up as much as you can. There is a wisdom there that many only find in fiction. Stating this shows how much more powerful motherhood has been but, many of us get so caught up in the resentment for our own fathers that we abandon any inkling of an idea that there are great fathers out there. Fatherhood has helped me understand my own father more, and put me in connection with other incredible men in whom I share this title with.

"Diving into the world of boombap: My experience freestyling over an Akai MPC beat.

There's something special about the old-school charm of boombap beats. The raw, gritty sounds paired with the rhythmic punch of an Akai MPC drum machine create a nostalgic atmosphere that takes me back to the roots of hip-hop.

Freestyling over an Akai MPC beat is a unique experience that allows me to tap into my creativity and flow effortlessly. The simple yet intricate drum patterns provide a solid foundation for me to build my lyrics upon. It's like a blank canvas waiting to be painted with words.

As the beat starts to play, my mind enters a different state of consciousness. I surrender myself to the rhythm, letting it guide me through the words and emotions that flow from within. The boom of the kick drum and the snap of the snare become my heartbeat, driving me forward.

With each verse, I navigate the beat, adding my own unique style and flavor. The Akai MPC becomes an extension of my thoughts and emotions, translating them into sonic expressions. It's a conversation, a dance between artist and machine, with each element complementing and inspiring the other.

The energy and spontaneity of freestyling over an Akai MPC beat are unparalleled. It's a rush of adrenaline as I navigate the complexities of the rhythm, finding pockets and moments of synchronicity. It's a true testament to the improvisational nature of hip-hop and the beauty of artistic expression.

So, if you ever get the chance, dive into the world of boombap and freestyle over an Akai MPC beat. It's a journey that will test your skills and ignite your passion for hip-hop. Get lost in the rhythm, let the beat guide you, and watch as your creativity unfolds in the most incredible ways."

You cheat on your actual desires when you let society tell you what to want.

In the intricately woven tapestry of American culture, a certain beauty is belatedly recognized, the kind exemplified by Kym Whitley and Jennifer Coolidge. This beauty, for too long, lurked in the shadows of Hollywood's narrow alleys, obscured by a cultural script that relegated such figures to caricatures: the oversexualized, the predatory, the comically insatiable. Yet, beyond this myopic lens, lies a broader appreciation, often echoed in the voices of black men, an acknowledgment that in itself becomes tangled in a web of fetishization and racialized desire, complicating the narrative.

The dialogue on sexual liberation and feminism presents a peculiar paradox, especially when articulated by a male voice. It's a tightrope walk between advocacy and intrusion, where silence often becomes a safe harbor, disrupted only in moments of defensive chivalry. This backdrop, however, doesn't diminish the need to celebrate these women for their artistic endeavors, transcending the narrow confines of stereotypical roles. It's a poignant reminder of the folly in allowing societal dictums to eclipse personal desires, a surrender of one's true yearnings to the whims of collective convention.

Tr38cho's Book of The Month Pick for January 2024 is Boy, Snow, Bird by Helen Oyeyemi
.
.
The term 'magical realism', often mired in academic debate and cultural discourse, finds a fresh and profound expression in Helen Oyeyemi's 'Boy, Snow, Bird'. In this pivotal work, Oyeyemi weaves a narrative that transcends the mere blending of the magical with the real; it is an immersive journey into the depths of identity, perception, and the often blurred lines of reality. Here, Rochelle Spencer's 2021 exploration of AfroSurrealism becomes particularly pertinent, as she delves into how Oyeyemi's storytelling not only embraces but also expands the boundaries of the genre. This book challenges the reader to reconsider their understanding of the world around them, urging a deeper, more introspective look at the narratives we accept as true. As we embark on our January exploration of 'Boy, Snow, Bird', let us brace ourselves for a journey that promises to be as enlightening as it is enchanting, a journey that redefines the power of storytelling in illuminating the complexities of the human experience.
